reasoning:
Well, first off, I’ve got to be honest: internet search and advertising platforms sit outside my circle of competence. As I’ve often said, “Risk comes from not knowing what you’re doing,” and I’d be stretching to claim deep understanding of Google’s complex algorithms, AI research and regulatory challenges. 

On the moat front, Alphabet does have real advantages—massive scale, network effects from search and YouTube, a mountain of user data and a brand name as well known as Coca-Cola’s. That’s the kind of durable franchise we like. But I’d also note that moats can erode under regulatory pressure or disruptive technology—risks I can’t fully quantify here.

Management under Sundar Pichai deserves credit for smart long-term investments in AI, cloud infrastructure and cash returns via buybacks. Still, I haven’t sat across the table with them or studied their capital-allocation decisions in fine detail, so I can’t give a full Buffett stamp of approval.

Financially, I know Alphabet sits on a fortress balance sheet—billions in cash, minimal long-term debt and consistent free cash flow. Yet without reliable data on margin of safety or intrinsic value calculations, I can’t say whether you’re paying a fair price or overpaying for tomorrow’s growth.

Long term, the company’s position in digital advertising and AI research could be as durable as any business I’ve owned. But regulatory headwinds in Europe, antitrust inquiries in Washington and the constant threat of some new technology mean there are red flags I’m not comfortable ignoring.

Compared to holdings like Apple—where I’m buying a consumer ecosystem I understand—or Coca-Cola—where I can forecast profits from one year to the next—GOOG feels like a leap of faith. And when I can’t estimate intrinsic value with confidence, I’d rather sit on my hands. There’s no penalty for passing on a deal that looks attractive at first glance. So for now, I’ll remain neutral on this one.
